453
00:31:02,627 --> 00:31:04,493
What about any other criteria?

454
00:31:04,563 --> 00:31:07,897
- No atherosclerotic vascular disease.
- Are there any...

455
00:31:07,966 --> 00:31:12,666
No pneumonia, no bacteremia.
No hep "B" or "C" or any other letters.

456
00:31:12,738 --> 00:31:14,832
Substance abuse. Any history...

457
00:31:14,906 --> 00:31:16,841
No alcohol. No drugs.

458
00:31:16,908 --> 00:31:21,107
Any psychiatric conditions? History
of depression? <i>She's a little blue.</i>

459
00:31:21,179 --> 00:31:25,116
But turns out she needs
a heart transplant, so...

460
00:31:32,424 --> 00:31:35,121
Dr. House, if you subvert
or mislead this committee,

461
00:31:35,193 --> 00:31:38,095
you will be subject
to disciplinary action.

462
00:31:43,168 --> 00:31:46,536
Dr. Cuddy, do you have
reason to think that I would lie?

463
00:31:46,605 --> 00:31:50,167
I simply want you to
answer the question.

464
00:31:50,242 --> 00:31:53,644
Is there anything on the
recipient exclusion criteria...

465
00:31:53,712 --> 00:31:57,877
that would disqualify your
patient from getting a heart?

466
00:32:08,627 --> 00:32:10,960
No.

467
00:32:18,136 --> 00:32:21,038
Beautiful organ donor weather.

468
00:32:21,106 --> 00:32:23,041
You lied, didn't you?

469
00:32:23,108 --> 00:32:25,509
I never lie. Big mistake.

470
00:32:25,577 --> 00:32:28,445
Then you should have voted
against putting her on the list.

471
00:32:28,513 --> 00:32:32,814
- You're my friend.
- Oh, geez, have some backbone.

472
00:32:32,884 --> 00:32:34,819
If you think I'm
wrong, do something.

473
00:32:34,886 --> 00:32:37,048
Wait. You're getting mad
at me for sticking up for you?

474
00:32:37,122 --> 00:32:41,116
You value our friendship more
than your ethical responsibilities.

475
00:32:41,193 --> 00:32:43,992
Our friendship is an
ethical responsibility.

476
00:32:49,134 --> 00:32:50,966
What is it?

477
00:32:52,471 --> 00:32:54,872
My patient's getting a heart.

478
00:33:07,586 --> 00:33:09,555
<i>He's not gonna fire you.</i>

479
00:33:09,621 --> 00:33:11,988
<i>I'd fire you. Bye-bye.</i>

480
00:33:13,758 --> 00:33:17,024
I screw up, the patient
dies, I'll never get another job.

481
00:33:17,095 --> 00:33:19,997
So stick your head between your
legs and go lick your wounds in Gstaad.

482
00:33:21,333 --> 00:33:23,359
Well, I like it here.

483
00:33:29,674 --> 00:33:32,887
You guys don't think it's weird House knew
the patient needed a heart transplant...

484
00:33:32,911 --> 00:33:34,880
before we did any heart tests?

485
00:33:36,014 --> 00:33:38,074
That's House. He knows things.

486
00:33:38,149 --> 00:33:40,015
<i>But usually he's
putting it in our face.</i>

487
00:33:40,085 --> 00:33:42,213
Telling us how
cleverly he figured it out.

488
00:33:42,287 --> 00:33:45,189
This time nothing.
Just had a hunch.

489
00:33:47,459 --> 00:33:49,394
That is weird.

490
00:34:21,793 --> 00:34:24,092
Cauterize that one bleeder.

491
00:34:28,900 --> 00:34:31,096
Okay, ready for the donor heart.

492
00:34:36,608 --> 00:34:39,942
They just stopped Carly's
heart, and your dumb patient...

493
00:34:40,011 --> 00:34:42,947
They're all— Oh, the guy who
can't talk. Mr. Van Der Meer.

494
00:34:43,014 --> 00:34:46,109
He's scheduled an appointment
to see you. Oh, goody.

495
00:34:48,486 --> 00:34:53,186
I wanted you to know Chase is
worried you're going to fire him.

496
00:34:53,258 --> 00:34:56,092
It's bad enough that
screw-ups cost lives.

497
00:34:56,161 --> 00:34:58,323
Now we've got Vogler,
screw-ups cost jobs.

498
00:34:58,396 --> 00:35:00,490
I want Chase scared.

499
00:35:00,565 --> 00:35:03,160
I want him doing everything
he can to protect his job.

500
00:35:03,234 --> 00:35:05,112
Dr. House, if you were in
his position, wouldn't you

501
00:35:05,136 --> 00:35:07,148
be more likely to perform
well if you were reassured...

502
00:35:07,172 --> 00:35:11,542
Oh, will you stop it with the
book? Why are you doing this?

503
00:35:12,644 --> 00:35:15,614
I'm not doing anything.
You're manipulating everyone.

504
00:35:18,550 --> 00:35:22,385
People... dismiss me.

505
00:35:23,421 --> 00:35:26,949
Because I'm a woman.
Because I'm pretty.

506
00:35:27,025 --> 00:35:30,484
Because... I'm not aggressive.

507
00:35:31,863 --> 00:35:35,732
My opinions shouldn't be rejected
just because people don't like me.

508
00:35:35,800 --> 00:35:37,496
They like you.

509
00:35:38,803 --> 00:35:40,704
Everyone likes you.

510
00:35:42,707 --> 00:35:44,471
Do you?

511
00:36:03,795 --> 00:36:05,764
I have to know.

512
00:36:07,065 --> 00:36:08,363
No.

513
00:36:16,775 --> 00:36:18,710
Okay.

514
00:36:36,761 --> 00:36:40,493
Five hours, 23
minutes. That's fast.

515
00:36:40,565 --> 00:36:43,091
Is that good or bad? It depends.

516
00:36:43,168 --> 00:36:46,468
Either surgery went really
well, or it ended really abruptly.

517
00:36:49,507 --> 00:36:52,375
Textbook. She'll outlive us all.

518
00:36:53,545 --> 00:36:55,480
Thank you.

519
00:37:01,152 --> 00:37:03,781
<i>Triage nurse,
pick up line 274 1.</i>

520
00:37:06,825 --> 00:37:09,954
So, sing for me.

521
00:37:13,164 --> 00:37:15,565
Oh, no, no, no,
no. Come on, look.

522
00:37:15,633 --> 00:37:17,631
When you had your
surgery, you were intubated.

523
00:37:17,655 --> 00:37:19,502
The surgeon stuck a
tube down your throat.

524
00:37:19,571 --> 00:37:22,735
Now, it never happens and it's
never caught, but it happened.

525
00:37:22,807 --> 00:37:27,336
Your vocal cords were paralyzed. I
treated the spastic dysphonia with Botox.

526
00:37:27,412 --> 00:37:30,678
Ironically, a substance that tightens
every other corner of your face.

527
00:37:30,749 --> 00:37:34,777
<i>It actually loosens the tongue. I
have healed you. You can talk.</i>

528
00:37:40,692 --> 00:37:42,627
Oh, well.

529
00:37:42,694 --> 00:37:44,663
Boo!

530
00:37:45,930 --> 00:37:48,832
Okay.

531
00:37:48,900 --> 00:37:51,995
You don't have to say anything.
It can be our little secret.

532
00:37:52,070 --> 00:37:55,529
If you can talk, blink twice.

533
00:37:58,443 --> 00:38:00,810
But you're not going to,

534
00:38:00,879 --> 00:38:03,162
because you think you
won't be entitled to the

535
00:38:03,186 --> 00:38:05,442
money you won in the
settlement with Simpson.

536
00:38:08,186 --> 00:38:10,553
Yesterday, I would have said
you had to give the money back.

537
00:38:10,622 --> 00:38:15,720
<i>Today, hospital's
come into a lot of money.</i>

538
00:38:15,794 --> 00:38:17,729
Mum's the word.

539
00:38:54,165 --> 00:38:56,327
Hey.

540
00:38:56,401 --> 00:38:58,336
Hey.

541
00:39:00,839 --> 00:39:04,105
I know the cardiologist has
given you some guidelines,

542
00:39:04,175 --> 00:39:07,339
a schedule of medication
and a strict diet.

543
00:39:07,412 --> 00:39:11,941
<i>Just what somebody with
an eating disorder needs.</i>

544
00:39:12,016 --> 00:39:14,747
So I thought I'd
get you started.

545
00:39:14,819 --> 00:39:17,288
Fried chicken from
the Carnegie Deli.

546
00:39:19,691 --> 00:39:22,092
- You're kidding.
- Yeah.

547
00:39:22,160 --> 00:39:24,095
Actually, I got it downstairs.

548
00:39:29,300 --> 00:39:32,702
Why did you fight for me?

549
00:39:32,770 --> 00:39:36,468
You risked so much,
and you hardly know me.

550
00:39:42,313 --> 00:39:44,248
You're my patient.

551
00:39:48,486 --> 00:39:51,752
Don't screw it up.

552
00:40:00,331 --> 00:40:04,427
<i>♪♪</i>

553
00:40:26,591 --> 00:40:30,494
<i>♪♪</i>

554
00:40:37,368 --> 00:40:39,496
Love this part!

555
00:40:43,574 --> 00:40:45,668
<i>♪♪</i>

556
00:40:45,743 --> 00:40:49,145
Okay. He ruined it.

557
00:40:49,213 --> 00:40:51,315
Just wanted to stop
by and introduce myself.

558
00:40:51,339 --> 00:40:53,514
I'm Edward Vogler, new
chairman of the board.

559
00:40:53,584 --> 00:40:55,519
In a way, I guess that
makes me your boss.

560
00:40:57,422 --> 00:41:01,723
I am sorry about the lab coat thing.
My dry cleaners just destroyed it.

561
00:41:03,528 --> 00:41:07,124
That was my very first heart transplant
committee meeting. Very exciting.

562
00:41:07,198 --> 00:41:10,498
<i>Trust me, Six Flags—
Way more exciting.</i>

563
00:41:10,568 --> 00:41:12,809
Your patient's very lucky
to have such a passionate

564
00:41:12,833 --> 00:41:14,699
doctor. Stands up for
what he believes in.

565
00:41:14,772 --> 00:41:16,741
Sweet of you to say.

566
00:41:16,808 --> 00:41:19,141
Yeah. Afraid you've
been duped though.

567
00:41:19,210 --> 00:41:23,511
The nurse found this
in the patient's purse.

568
00:41:28,286 --> 00:41:31,154
Oh, my. If only I'd known.

569
00:41:31,222 --> 00:41:34,659
Tough being a doctor,
having all that power.

570
00:41:34,726 --> 00:41:36,661
The power to play God.

571
00:41:36,728 --> 00:41:40,756
Yes. I don't envy the transplant
committee their responsibility.

572
00:41:40,832 --> 00:41:44,599
They basically would have
been forced to kill that poor girl.

573
00:41:44,669 --> 00:41:46,763
I'm not sure I could
have done that.

574
00:41:48,339 --> 00:41:50,865
This is not a game
to me, Dr. House.

575
00:41:50,942 --> 00:41:55,903
No. It's actually more like
we're dancing right now.

576
00:41:55,980 --> 00:41:58,006
So let's get to the
point. You don't like me.

577
00:41:58,082 --> 00:42:01,712
I'm pretty sure I'm not gonna
like you. It's nothing personal.

578
00:42:01,786 --> 00:42:04,449
I don't like anybody.

579
00:42:04,522 --> 00:42:06,457
But none of that
really matters, does it?

580
00:42:06,524 --> 00:42:09,255
Because you've got
money, and I've got tenure.

581
00:42:09,327 --> 00:42:13,560
You need full board approval
to get rid of me. I've got Cuddy.

582
00:42:13,631 --> 00:42:16,100
Right. And Wilson.

583
00:42:16,167 --> 00:42:19,763
So, as long as we're
stuck with each other,

584
00:42:19,837 --> 00:42:22,033
we might as well
ignore each other.

585
00:42:22,106 --> 00:42:25,372
<i>♪♪</i>

586
00:42:26,444 --> 00:42:28,379
<i>♪♪</i>

587
00:42:28,446 --> 00:42:30,472
That wasn't nearly as
dramatic as I was hoping.

588
00:42:34,385 --> 00:42:37,355
I looked into that tenure
thing, and you're right.

589
00:42:37,422 --> 00:42:41,086
It's actually easier for me to get rid of
a board member like Cuddy or Wilson...

590
00:42:41,159 --> 00:42:43,594
than to get rid of a doctor.

591
00:42:43,661 --> 00:42:46,790
That's interesting, isn't it?

592
00:44:09,380 --> 00:44:10,643
That's some bad hat, Harry.
